 the 1980s by numerous outbreaks and scares involving salmonella in lettuce and eggs, listeria in cheese, the links between vCJD and BSE, E.Coli 0157 in cooked meats, and foot and mouth disease. Yet, as this book shows, the various issues involved were important as early as 1963/4, when there were serious typhoid outbreaks in Harlow, South Shields,Bedford, and Aberdeen, traced to contaminated corned beef imported from Argentina. Based upon extensive research, using archives which have only recently become available, private papers, and interviews as well as secondary literature, the book analyses the course of the outbreak and looks at the responses of politicians, officials, health professionals, business interests, the media and the public. It also considers the difficult issue of the weighing offood safety against international trade and other business and economic interests; conflicts between government departments; rivalry between professionals such as doctors and veterinarians; the effects upon and influence of victims and local communities; and the conduct of and responses to an official enquiry. Overall, it draws out generic lessons for how such epidemics should be handled, adding an historical perspective to contemporary debates.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCorned beefzGreat Britain. 0aFood contaminationxGovernment policyzGreat Britain. 0aFood poisoningzGreat Britain. 0aTyphoid feverzGreat BritainxEpidemiology. 4aHistory of Science & Medicine. 4aModern History. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh1 aDiack, H. Lesley, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPennington, T. Hugh, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSmith, David F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell